#4.What about Promises?
<ul><li><div class="fragment">Promises serve almost the same purpose as RxJS Observables</li><li><div class="fragment">Problems with Promises:</li><ul><li><div class="fragment">Chaining Promises</li><li><div class="fragment">Canceling Promises</li></ul></ul><br><br><br>
#RxJS to the rescue!
#1. Observables
<ul><li><div class="fragment">Building blocks of FRP in RxJS<br></li><li><div class="fragment">First class objects to represent Asynchronous Data<br></li><li><div class="fragment">Operators with fabulous Functional Grammar</li><li><div class="fragment">Interoperable with other sync/async data</li></ul><br><div class="fragment"><pre><i class="fa fa-lightbulb-o"></i> An Observable is an event stream which can emit zero or more events, and may or may not finish.&nbsp;<br>If it finishes, then it does so by either emitting an error or&nbsp;a special “complete” event.</pre>
#1. Arrays Are iterable
<div class="fragment"><br><pre>```js
Array&nbsp; .of(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)&nbsp; .map(x => x * x)&nbsp; .filter(x => x%2 === 0)&nbsp; .reduce((x, acc) => x + acc)
```</pre>
#2.Observables are iterables
<div class="fragment"><br></pre>```
Observable&nbsp; .of(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)&nbsp; .map(x => x * x)&nbsp; .filter(x => x%2 === 0)&nbsp; .reduce((x, acc) => x + acc)
```</pre><br><div class="fragment"><br><pre><i class="fa fa-lightbulb-o"></i> Remember:&nbsp;we return a new Observable every time we do any transformation</pre><br>
#3.Observables are lazy
<pre>```js
let users_ = getUsersObservable();<br>let notJohnConners_ =&nbsp;&nbsp; users_&nbsp; &nbsp; .map(user => user.fullName)&nbsp; &nbsp; .map(name => name.first + ' ' + name.last)&nbsp; &nbsp; .filter(x => x === 'John Connor');<br>notJohnConners_.subscribe(&nbsp;(user) => console.log('New user arrived: ', user),&nbsp;(error) => console.log('Error Occured', error),&nbsp;() => console.log('All Done'))
```</pre>
#4.You can make anything into an observable
#1.Arrays
<pre><br>```js
var a = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];var a$ = Observable.from(a);var b$ = Observable.of(1, 2, 3);
```</pre> &nbsp; &nbsp;
#2.Promises
<pre><br>```js
var a = iPromiseOfSomething();var a_ = Observable.fromPromise(a);
```</pre>
#3.Events
<pre class="fragment"><br>```js
var result = document&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;.getElementById('result');var source =&nbsp;Rx.Observable.fromEvent(result, 'click');<br>var observer = Rx.Observer.create(&nbsp; &nbsp; function (x) {&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; console.log('Next: ' + x);&nbsp; &nbsp; },&nbsp; &nbsp; function (err) {&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; console.log('Error: ' + err);&nbsp; &nbsp; },&nbsp; &nbsp; function () {&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; console.log('Completed');&nbsp; &nbsp; });source.subscribe(observer)
```</pre><pre class="fragment"><i class="fa fa-lightbulb-o"></i> Rx will truncate multiple arguments from events,&nbsp;you can use the selector function to combine all of them</b></pre>
#4.Callbacks
<pre><br>```js
writeFile = require('fs').writeFile;<br>wf_ = Observable&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; .fromNodeCallback(writeFile);
```</pre>
#5.Custom Observables
<ul><li><div class="fragment">Similar to resolve and reject in Promises</li><li><div class="fragment">We can create custom observables</li><li><div class="fragment">We have three functions: OnNext, OnComplete, OnError</li></ul><div class="fragment"><pre><br>```js
var source = Rx.Observable.create(function (observer) {&nbsp; observer.onNext(42);<br>&nbsp; observer.onCompleted();<br>&nbsp; return function () {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; console.log('disposed');&nbsp; }});var subscription = source.subscribe(&nbsp; function (x) { console.log('onNext: %s', x); },&nbsp; function (e) { console.log('onError: %s', e); },&nbsp; function () { console.log('onCompleted'); });<br>subscription.dispose();
```</pre>
#5. You can combine multiple Observables
<pre>```js
var api1 = "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=query&amp;prop=extracts&amp;format=json&amp;exintro=&amp;titles=Stack%20Overflow";var api2 = "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=query&amp;prop=extracts&amp;format=json&amp;exintro=&amp;titles=Computer%20Science";<br>var promise1 = $.get(api1);var promise2 = $.get(api2);<br>var source1 =&nbsp;Rx.Observable.fromPromise(promise1);<br>var source2=&nbsp;Rx.Observable.fromPromise(promise2);<br>var combined = Rx.Observable.concat(source1,source2);
```</pre>
#Reactive Programming
<ul><li><div class="fragment">RxJS is Based on the observer and iterator patterns<br></li><li><div class="fragment">Reactive can be explained as: <br></li><ul><li><div class="fragment">Module Foo and Module Bar<br></li><li><div class="fragment">Module Bar is said to be reactive when it listens to modules Foo's changes</li><li><div class="fragment">Foo doesn't know that Bar exists!</li></ul></ul>

#Excercise
<pre>```
test('querying over events', function () {&nbsp; var results = 0;<br>&nbsp; var e = new EventEmitter();<br>&nbsp; Observable.fromEvent(e, 'click')&nbsp; &nbsp; .filter(function (click) { return click.x === click.y })&nbsp; &nbsp; .map(function (click) { return __ + __; })&nbsp; &nbsp; .subscribe(function (x) { results = x; });<br>&nbsp; e.emit('click', {x: 100, y: 50});&nbsp; e.emit('click', {x: 75, &nbsp;y: 75});&nbsp; e.emit('click', {x: 40, &nbsp;y: 80});<br>&nbsp; equal(results, 150);<br>// fill in the __ inside map<br><br>});
```<br></pre>
